  <static seed="1583" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations20.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{1}{4t}-\frac{1}{3t}}={1}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{-1}{12}\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{12t}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{1}{4t}-\frac{1}{3t}} \amp = {1} \\
  {\frac{1}{4t}\cdot 12t-\frac{1}{3t}\cdot 12t} \amp = {1\cdot 12t} \\
  3 - 4 \amp = {12t} \\
  -1 \amp = {12t} \\
  \frac{-1}{12} \amp = \frac{{12t}}{12} \\
  {\left\{\frac{-1}{12}\right\}} \amp = t \\
  t \amp  = {\left\{\frac{-1}{12}\right\}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>t \ne 0</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>t = {\left\{\frac{-1}{12}\right\}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
